  <h1>How to Adopt a Pre-Threshold Contractual License</h1>
  <p class="small" style="margin-top:0.2rem; margin-bottom:0.35rem;">
    <strong>Operational adoption guide for institutions, sponsors, and pilot partners</strong>
  </p>
  <h2>A concise pathway to implement pre-threshold governance in contract design — without turning it into ESG scoring, policy mandates, or outcome certification.</h2>

  <div class="meta">
    c-ECO Doctrine — Contractual Equity &amp; Ecological Co-Responsibility<br>
    For institutional use: sponsors • grant-makers • pilot partners<br>
    Date: 2025
  </div>

  <hr>

  <h3>What “license” means (and what it does not)</h3>
  <p>
    In c-ECO, a <strong>Pre-Threshold Contractual License</strong> is not a regulatory authorization, a public-law permit, or a product sold by a private actor.
    It is a <strong>voluntary contractual governance architecture</strong> adopted by contracting parties to preserve reversibility and institutional decision-space over time.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p style="margin:0;">
      <strong>Core idea:</strong><br>
      The ongoing exercise of certain contractual powers remains effective only if pre-threshold governance procedures are activated and documented when credible signals of systemic instability emerge.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p class="small">
    The license is about <em>procedural governability</em> — not outcome guarantees, ESG performance, or policy compliance.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h3>When a Pre-Threshold Contractual License is appropriate</h3>
  <p>
    The license is designed for contracts that structure long-term trajectories under cumulative risk and potential irreversibility.
    It is particularly relevant where contracts can silently produce <em>lock-in</em> before any breach or illegality occurs.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Long duration:</strong> multi-year commitments, renewals, take-or-pay, exclusivity, concessions.</li>
    <li><strong>Expansion authority:</strong> scale-up rights, escalation mechanisms, capacity increases, scope creep.</li>
    <li><strong>Path dependency:</strong> data/AI systems, algorithmic governance, infrastructure dependencies, supply-chain rigidity.</li>
    <li><strong>Threshold exposure:</strong> ecological, infrastructural, systemic, or governance thresholds where reversibility erodes early.</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <h3>The adoption pathway (5 steps)</h3>

  <p><strong>Step 1 — Scope the contract’s “licensed powers”</strong></p>
  <p class="small">
    Identify which contractual powers, if exercised over time, can produce irreversible trajectories or consume future decision-space.
    Typical “licensed powers” include expansion rights, escalation mechanisms, automatic renewals, exclusivity, termination asymmetries, and lock-in clauses.
  </p>

  <p><strong>Step 2 — Define credible pre-threshold signals (without technocracy)</strong></p>
  <p class="small">
    Establish credible indicators that trigger procedural reassessment. c-ECO does not require courts to adjudicate scientific thresholds;
    instead, it frames <em>governance triggers</em> that activate contractual procedures when instability or loss of reversibility becomes credibly observable.
  </p>

  <p><strong>Step 3 — Embed pre-threshold procedures through the c-ECO Clause</strong></p>
  <p class="small">
    Use the c-ECO Clause to translate the license into contractual language: reassessment, justification, documentation, and — where appropriate — recalibration,
    as conditions evolve. The Clause conditions <em>effectiveness</em> of the relevant powers, not the contract’s validity.
  </p>

  <p><strong>Step 4 — Assign internal institutional roles</strong></p>
  <p class="small">
    Determine who owns the process (legal, governance, risk) and how decisions are recorded. The license works when the institution can show
    that it preserved governability through traceable procedure — not by claiming perfect foresight.
  </p>

  <p><strong>Step 5 — Optional: seek verification via the c-ECO Pre-Threshold Contract Seal</strong></p>
  <p class="small">
    After adoption, organizations may seek the Seal to verify that contractual architecture incorporates pre-threshold governance standards.
    The Seal does not certify outcomes; it verifies that the governance design exists and is structured for temporal validity.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h3>Model “license language” (high-level)</h3>
  <p class="small">
    This is not a full clause. It is a short example of how a license is expressed as a condition of ongoing effectiveness.
  </p>

  <div class="box">
    <div class="label">Model license condition (conceptual)</div>
    <pre><code>The Parties agree that specified contractual powers with potential lock-in effects shall remain effective over time only if,
upon credible signals of rising systemic instability or loss of reversibility, the Parties activate and document pre-threshold governance procedures,
including reassessment, justification, and (where appropriate) recalibration of execution, in good faith.</code></pre>
  </div>

  <hr>

  <h3>What institutions receive from adoption</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Governance optionality:</strong> preserves intervention capacity while it still matters.</li>
    <li><strong>Lower dispute intensity:</strong> procedural traceability reduces “surprise collapse” litigation.</li>
    <li><strong>Portfolio comparability:</strong> enables consistent review of long-term contractual risk.</li>
    <li><strong>Grant/sponsor alignment:</strong> converts theory into a bounded, testable implementation pathway.</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <h3>How to engage with c-ECO</h3>
  <p>
    If your institution is interested in adopting a Pre-Threshold Contractual License through a pilot or applied research participation,
    you can submit an Expression of Interest.
  </p>
  <p class="small" style="letter-spacing:0.10em; opacity:0.65;">
    → <a href="applied-study.html"><strong>Participate in the c-ECO Applied Study</strong></a>
  </p>

